SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The corporation is exempt from corporate Federal income taxes under Section 501 (c) (3) of the Internal Revenue Code and from Mississippi income taxes. Therefore, no provision has been made for Federal or Mississippi corporate income taxes in the accompanying financial statements. In addition, the Organization has been determined by the Internal Revenue Service not to be a "private foundation" within the meaning of Section 509 (a) of the Code. The Organization has analyzed its tax position taken for filings with the Internal Revenue. It believes that its tax filing positions will be sustained upon examination and does not anticipate any adjustments that would result in a material adverse effect on its financial condition, results of operations, or cash flows. The Organization's federal and state income tax returns for adopted recently issued accounting principles related to uncertain tax positions for 2022, 2021, and 2020 are subject to examination by the federal, state and local taxing authorities, generally for three years after they are filed.

The Form 990 is first reviewed by the CEO and CFO. Afterwhich, it is presented for review by the Finance Committee of the Board of Directors. From there, it is presented for review and approval to the entire Board of Directors.
All employees and board members are required to complete and attest annually. All staff and board members are included in training sessions annually where policy violations are covered.
The CEO, CFO and other key employees' compensation is approved by the Board of Directors.
The Board of Directors, along with the recommendation of the CEO, approves compensation for other employees.
The Organization's Conflict of Interest policy and financial statements are available to the public upon request.
Other changes in net assets, principle payment of loan and acquisition on property and equipment.
